\begin_layout Section
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is still an outstanding question of biology how cells work together to
 build large scale tissues.
 Whilst cells individually are constrained to the two simple fates of division
 or eventual death, it is poorly understood how cells might work in concert
 to synchronise and regulate their fates 
\emph on
in situ
\emph default
 to grow, maintain, or repair tissue, or further how failures of such regulation
 lead to failure or cancer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Traditionally, the problem has been tackled with a reductionist approach
 of explicating the molecular mechanism within cells.
 In particular, a large body of work now exist which delineate the various
 gene and protein expression networks that modify cell fate.
 A central challenge to this effort is the vast complexity of the uncovered
 biochemical networks, which confound attempts to identify simple principles
 and concepts which interact in predictable ways to allow comprehension
 and prediction of a range of observations.
 Instead, often the clearest biochemical dissection occur very far from
 a typical environment, leading to difficulties, for example, in translating
 cell fate choice in culture to that during regular maintenance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead, the work of Klein and Simons advocated a more phenomenological
 approach, where by directly measuring and mathematically modelling quantitative
 characteristics of tissues it becomes possible to infer the relevant underlying
 dynamics of cells.
 Typically, one would focus on behaviours which arise because of the large
 number of cells and their interactions, which are robust to small changes
 of the underlying cell-resolution biochemistry.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Clayton2007"

\end_inset

 showed that with modern techniques such as inducible genetic labelling
 and confocal microscopy, it is indeed possible to collect such data and
 carry out the program for interfollicular epidermis (IFE) in normal maintenance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In that case, cells in the IFE were modelled as non-interacting, each cell
 independently choosing when to divide or permanently differentiate and
 leave the basal layer.
 The study of such systems has a long tradition in mathematical biology,
 under the title of branching processes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Athreya2004"

\end_inset

.
 A crucial theorem of that theory states that: assuming a population of
 cells which maintain their number (i.e.
 homoeostatic or in equilibrium), if one were to label a single cell and
 count its progeny (a clone), then in the interesting case where some of
 that clone continue to proliferate, their number would eventually (on average)
 increase linearly with time, 
\emph on
independent of any other features of those cells
\emph default
.
 In corollary, the chance of such a surviving clone must decrease as one
 over time.
 In particular, one makes no assumption about distributions of cell cycle
 lengths, or the precise hierarchy leading from self-proliferation to differenti
ation.
 The only assumptions are independence and homoeostasis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is in fact an example of 
\emph on
universal behaviour
\emph default
, a term borrowed from statistical physics to describe phenomena which only
 occur in the presence of sufficiently large number of particles (here,
 cells), and which do not depend on microscopic details, but rather on symmetrie
s and dimensionality of the situation.
 Such robustness of prediction allows for easy confirmation in experiments,
 and indeed precisely this linear scaling was a central argument in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Clayton2007"

\end_inset

 as part of the evidence that there existed a fast-cycling, self-renewing
 population of progenitors in IFE.
 Note that it is only the linear scaling which is universal: the rate at
 which the clone can be expected to grow is not, and will depend in complex
 ways on the microscopic details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, one might wonder about the assumption of independence.
 Whilst relying on statistical averaging to achieve homoeostasis is nice
 in theory, one cannot but feel that some negative feedback loop would be
 more stable, especially in the presence of injury.
 A simple model might be that of cells which differentiate and leave behind
 a hole, which is filled by one of its neighbours --- as might be expected
 for contact inhibition of progenitors.
 Such models are known in the mathematical literature as 
\emph on
voter models
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CLIFFORD1973"

\end_inset

.
 If one imagines labelling each cell individually, a differentiating cell
 getting replaced is the same as if that cell simply changed its label to
 that of its neighbour --- analogous to how opinions spread in a group of
 weak-willed voters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In analogy to our one-cell derived clone in the branching process, we can
 ask what happens to a single labelled cell in a sea of unlabelled cells.
 It is known 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bramson1980"

\end_inset

 that the answer depends crucially on the dimension of the space that the
 cells live in.
 Assuming that the clone survives, at large times: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
in 1D, the size eventually grows as square root of time: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[n|n>0\right]\sim\sqrt{t}$
\end_inset

;
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Notation: 
\begin_inset Formula $f\sim g$
\end_inset

 means that in the appropriate limit, 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g\in\Theta\left(c\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
in 2D, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[n|n>0\right]\sim t/\log\left(t\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
and in 3D (or, as a mathematical extension, above 3D), 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[n|n>0\right]\sim t$
\end_inset

, just as if there were no interactions at all.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively, in low dimensions, a cell is likely to be replaced by a cell
 of the same label, leading to a sort of jamming where the boundary of the
 clone does not grow very fast; in higher dimensions, a cell will be replaced
 by a randomly labelled cell, and so each division will look very much random,
 and indistinguishable from a non-interacting situation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be precise, the results above have only been mathematically proven in
 square lattices, and a few others regular lattices (hexagonal, for instance).
 However, a body of numerical and theoretical work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bramson1979,Ben-Naim1996,Dornic2001,Dornic2005,Canet2005"

\end_inset

 suggest that the scaling is in fact universal, and do not depend on the
 details of the geometry, or how the interaction works exactly.
 For instance, it may be that cells are replaced not by immediate neighbours,
 but rather by any within a few cell diameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The one dimensional case appears to be realised in spermatozoa generation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Klein2010"

\end_inset

, where the germ line stem cells are confined to tubes and exhibit contact
 inhibition.
 It has been hypothesised 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Klein2008"

\end_inset

 that in the IFE may exihibit the 2-dimensional case, but fundamentally,
 the extra factor of
\begin_inset Formula $\log\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is too close to a constant for achievable experiments to be seen: at short
 times, the jamming has not really set in and clone sizes still scale as
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, and once the dynamics approaches the universal limit (which may take months),
 
\begin_inset Formula $t/\log\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 between 1 month and 12 months is not easily distinguishable from a linear
 function of time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Limits of universality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whilst universal scaling is very useful for confirming that a particular
 choice of basic symmetries and assumptions is sufficient to describe an
 experiment, its very robustness against all manners of perturbations becomes
 a liability when one wishes to extract from experiment some quantitative
 measurements of the underlying process.
 For instance, whilst in mouse IFE it is possible to measure the non-universal
 rate constant associated with linear scaling of surviving clone sizes,
 that constant is not related to the underlying cell-scale dynamics in an
 obvious manner.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our view is that in addition to verifying the universal properties of a
 model, one should also verify some non-universal properties, ideally with
 the view of being able to 
\emph on
infer
\emph default
 the parameters from data.
 In particular, due to the difficulty of obtaining observations, the inference
 must be efficient, and maximally use the information contained in a relatively
 small number of observations.
\end_layout

