\begin_layout Standard
Previous collaboration between the Jones group and AMK and BDS 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Clayton2007,Klein2007,Doupe2010"

\end_inset

 focused on interfollicular epidermis (IFE) in mice.
 The IFE is a simple tissue, composed of multiple layers of keratinocytes,
 sitting atop a membrane that separates it from the rest of the muscle and
 mucosa that forms a substrate.
 Proliferation is confined to the basal layer of cells; upon differentiation,
 the cells stratify from the basal layer, lose their nucleus and much cellular
 machinery to turn into large, flat cells which are no longer transcriptionally
 active.
 As such, it is suited as a relatively clean environment in which to dissect
 the functional behaviour of cells with regards to their fate choice, via
 lineage tracing by inducible genetic labelling techniques.
 Specifically, they used genetically modified mice which carry an fluorescent
 protein gene, muted by a stop-cassette; upon treatment with tamoxifen the
 gene is activated by deletion of the stop cassette, leading to the production
 of the dye in that cell and all its progeny.
 By using a very low does of tamoxifen, it is possible to reduce the rate
 of induction such that fluorescent cells are widely spaced, and thus at
 some later time each cluster of fluorescent progeny (henceforth referred
 to as clonal cluster, or clone) can be assumed to have come from a single
 progenitor.
 It is then possible to measure by counting the distribution of clone sizes.
 Their work demonstrated the existence of a fast-turnover, equipotent population
 of progenitors which is capable of maintaining the tissue.
 This was in direct contrast to textbook models of long-lived stem cells
 supporting columns of more differentiated cells, via a hierarchy of transit-amp
lifying cells, capped by large plates of terminally differentiated cells.
 In particular, the evidence rests on: visual observation of large, single-cell
 derived clones with rough boundaries
