\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have shown that there is a population of progenitors in oesophageal epitheliu
m which maintains the tissue, which can be quantitatively modelled by a
 simple stochastic branching process.
 The progenitors divide at a constant rate and chose one of three fates
 with fixed probabilities; differentiated cells stratify and eventually
 shed.
 The model contains four parameters: the EP cell division rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, the ratio of symmetric to asymmetric cell divisions controlled by the
 parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, the stratification rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, and the loss rate of cells from tissue 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 The latter is fixed by the ratio of basal to suprabasal cells, which may
 be accurately measured; the other three were measured from observed clone
 size distributions.
 Moreover, we have shown that this model can capture the effect of atRA
 treatment through a straightforward adjustment of the average EP cell division
 rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is interesting to note we have evidence that 
\begin_inset Formula $r\neq\frac{1}{4}$
\end_inset

 (with very high confidence), which implies that the fate of sister cells
 are not independent.
 In other words, it is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 the case that a progenitor divides and each daughter cell independently
 chooses to differentiate.
 As such, either the decision is made prior to division (potentially via
 some asymmetric division of nuclear material) or post-mitosis by mutual
 inhibition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An obvious extension of the present model is to incorporate some interaction
 effect between cells.
 As noted in the Introduction, such a model would naturally fall into the
 voter model universality class, which has the same exponential clone size
 distribution, but with a characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $t/\log(t)$
\end_inset

 scaling for average surviving clone size.
 The data here does not support such a scaling relation, although it is
 possible that in the asymptotic regime where 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is large, the extra factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\log(t)$
\end_inset

 is too close to a constant to be experimentally distinguished.
 Furthermore, if the interactions extend over 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 cell diameters, then the asymptotic regime will be delayed by a time 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda d$
\end_inset

 which will remove traces of it from the short time behaviour (whilst the
 typical clone radius is smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, it does not know that the tissue is 2-dimensionally, and behaves in the
 mean-field fashion).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combined with the qualitative biological observations mentioned in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:ee-background-and-motivation"

\end_inset

, we believe these progenitors to be the totality of proliferating cells
 in the oesophageal epithelium, and are responsible for repair by switching
 reversibly to a different program of fate choice, biased towards proliferation.
 Furthermore, we conjecture that this mechanism is common to all keratinising
 stratified epithelia, such as IFE, though there may also be separate population
s of stem cells or progenitors which exist in particular anatomic niches.
 The quantitative behaviour is probably not universal, as far as the parameters
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 are concerned, though it would be interesting if any of them turn out to
 be; clearly, accurate measurements of these parameters across a range of
 tissues is an immediate direction for future work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We further conjecture that there are a discrete number of such proliferation
 programs, as opposed to continuously adjustable parameters, based on the
 admittedly aesthetic belief that it is so important that maintenance is
 properly homoeostatic (since any deviation would need to be exponentially
 small to be survivable over a finite lifespan) that it is precisely prescribed
 by a separate underlying chemical pathway.
 In other words, there exist distinct phases of cell kinetics, which may
 be amenable to similar quantitative analysis.
 So far, we have only elucidated the behaviour of the homoeostatic phase,
 and have observed for the first time the repair phase 
\emph on
in vivo
\emph default
.
 Quantitative understanding of the latter should be a rich arena for future
 work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also take this opportunity to comment on an issue not in the published
 literature at all.
 In previous work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Clayton2007,Doupe2010"

\end_inset

, the parameters of the model were estimated in a different manner.
 Recall that to define the model one needs three measurements.
 The overall asymptotic rate 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\tau=r\lambda/\rho$
\end_inset

 was estimated from the asymptotic regime, and could be measured with reasonable
 accuracy.
 The proportion of progenitors in the basal layer 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 was estimated by means of cell markers, in particular Ki67 was used as
 a marker for proliferation; this choice is fairly standard in work on keratinoc
ytes.
 This gave the combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $r\lambda$
\end_inset

, and the final parameter was chosen to make the short-time, non-universal
 clone distribution agree with experiment.
 In the ear, this gave 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=22\%$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=8\%$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\lambda\approx0.9\,\textrm{weeks}$
\end_inset

, a rate which agreed with existing estimates from more direct measurements.
 It was discovered early on in the course of this work that a similar procedure
 in oesophagus did 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
yield a sensible rate for the mean progenitor lifetime, especially in the
 presence of atRA; the discrepancy could be repaired if one assumed that
 Ki67 staining underestimates 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Careful experiments involving simultaneous staining of Ki67 and EdU in
 various pulse-chase scenarios confirmed that Ki67 was unreliable as an
 indicator of proliferation.
 Our private theory revolves around its specific role in RNA transcription,
 specifically how fast it turns off once commitment to differentiation is
 made; it is plausible that during an extended period after the decision
 is made, the cell is still transcriptionally active as it completely changes
 its behaviour.
 We hypothesized that the bias is worse in faster cycling tissues --- oesophagus
 in normal state has 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\lambda=0.5\,\textrm{weeks}$
\end_inset

 which decreases further to almost quarter of a week with atRA.
 Indeed, it was partially this problem which motivated the methodology eventuall
y taken, which infers the parameters of the model completely independently
 from any biological markers, but purely from the observed fate outcome
 in terms of clone sizes; the cost is the need to gather not only the distributi
on of number of basal cells, but the joint distribution with suprabasal
 cells as well.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a general point, we believe that this pivot away from biological markers
 is a good thing, and complementary to existing practices.
 Fundamentally, there is no such thing as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

proliferation marker
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

differentiation marker
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, or indeed for that matter 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

keratinocyte
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 versus 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hematopoietic marker
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 They are simple antibodies which attach to particular molecules that we
 have imposed a narrative upon.
 Those molecules exist momentarily, but we try to assign teleological function
 to them; we should not be amazed that this can work, and not surprised
 when it fails a little.
 Many experiments, for instance in the context of cancer, rely on the qualitativ
e response from Ki67 as evidence of greater or lesser proliferation.
 What we have observed is that in the limit of very fast cycle, the link
 between proliferation and Ki67 response decouples and cannot be trusted
 on a quantitative level.
 The Jones group is continuing this line of investigation, and trying to
 find more robust candidates for detecting proliferation, using the parameters
 derived in this work as the baseline for comparison.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Theorems on 1-Type Super-critical Branching Processes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As mentioned in Chapter 1, there is a remarkable theorem that, in the long
 time limit for a 
\emph on
critical branching process
\emph default
 (where each cell leave on average the exact same number of cells in the
 next generation), the scaled clone size distribution is exponential and
 the average clone size conditioned on survival grows linearly with time.
 The statement makes no other assumptions, and is a prototypical example
 of universality.
 Observation of this universality was crucial, in epithelia, to strongly
 suggest that such a simple stochastic process is possible for generating
 the tissue.
 Further observation of the expected non-universal helps to confirm, as
 well as elucidate some finer aspects of the process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If instead of exactly replenishing the number of proliferating cells, on
 average the number of cells increase, then we have a 
\emph on
super-critical process
\emph default
; then, as one might naively expect, the average clone size increases without
 bound, exponentially as a function of time.
 Whilst an exact exponential cannot be sustained for any period of time
 in a biologically realistic scenario, we might hope that it persists for
 long enough that we can be satisfied that there is an underlying stochastic
 process, i.e.
 perhaps an order of magnitude between transient non-universal behaviour
 on the order of a few cell cycles, and eventual limits of growth due to
 space or nutrients, some tens of cell cycles later.
 In particular, we are thinking of cancer like proliferation, both in live
 animals and in culture, where potentially a breakdown in the regulatory
 mechanism particularly lends itself to such a model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From informal discussions with the Jones group regarding possible mechanisms
 of regulatory failure, various experiments circumstantially implicated
 a failure to differentiate as a crucial step.
 Specifically, we expected to see progenitor cells 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

attempt
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to differentiate, but then fall back into cycle after a long period of
 apparent quiescence.
 Note that this behaviour care be fairly subtle: it is very easy for the
 
\emph on
typical
\emph default
 (median) or even 
\emph on
average
\emph default
 (mean) cell cycle to be unaffected to within experimental error, yet for
 the overall process to diverge dramatically from homoeostasis.
 Thus, it is absolutely necessary to be able to measure the 
\emph on
distribution
\emph default
 of cell cycles, or at the very least find evidence of particularly long
 cycles compared to the typical one.
 However, direct measurement of the distribution is problematic, especially
 in live animals, but even 
\emph on
in vitro
\emph default
.
 Given a typical cell cycle of days to weeks, direct imaging is almost impossibl
e.
 Cunning combinations of multiple simultaneous pulse-chase protocols may
 be sufficient, but aside from difficulties in gathering sufficient data
 (multiply labelled cells from low-level induction events are rare), one
 also experiences contaminating side-effects of prolonged exposure to fundamenta
lly mutagenic reagents such as BrdU (5-bromo-2'-deoxyuridine).
 Given our experience with clone size distributions, we thus became interested
 in the link between cell cycle times and the limit distribution of (scaled)
 clone sizes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Concretely, let a branching process be composed of equipotent cells, with
 lifetime distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Upon division, each cell with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}$
\end_inset

 will yield 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 daughters: we will consider generalised cells in this chapter; realistically
 
\begin_inset Formula $k\le2$
\end_inset

.
 Let us package that into a generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)=\sum_{k}p_{k}s^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 We will restrict ourselves to biologically feasible processes, in particular
 we will require all moments of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to exist.
 Furthermore, we will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, as it simplifies the consideration by avoiding total death of the clone;
 for any given 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 we can construct a 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\star}$
\end_inset

 of equal order such that no death occurs, with the only difference being
 the existence of terminal clones (see appendix
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:condition-survival"

\end_inset

).
 We also exclude certain pathological behaviours from consideration, such
 as the possibility for a clone to reach infinite size in finite time, which
 excludes in particular the existence of a Dirac delta spike at zero in
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 The average number of progeny per cell is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}kp_{k}=f^{\prime}(1)$
\end_inset

, and for a super-critical process 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}(1)>1$
\end_inset

, which we will assume for the rest of this chapter.
 There are then some classic theorems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Athreya2004"

\end_inset

 about such processes: the average clone size diverges exponentially with
 a 
\emph on
Malthusian-rate 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left[f,g\right]$
\end_inset

 defined to be the (only) positive root of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{\prime}(1)\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-\alpha y}g(y)\, dy=1;
\]

\end_inset

and in the limit of infinite time, the distribution (normalised to unit
 mean) of the total number of cells converges to a distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)$
\end_inset

, whose characteristic function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)=\mathbb{E}\left[e^{iuW}\right]$
\end_inset

 is the unique solution (amongst distributions with unit mean) of
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi(u)=\int_{0}^{\infty}f\left[\phi\left(ue^{-\alpha y}\right)\right]g(y)\, dy.\label{eq:forwards-eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Notice that since the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 sets a scale for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, we may remove it by scaling 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with no change to the limiting behaviour.
 Therefore without loss of generality we shall set 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whilst the general result has been known for a while, specific solutions
 to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

 are not manifold.
 The literature is mostly concerned with the case when the process is 
\emph on
Markovian
\emph default
, either in discrete time (
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)=\delta(t-\tau)$
\end_inset

 for some constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

), or continuous time 
\begin_inset Formula $(g(t)=e^{-t/\tau}$
\end_inset

 ); in particular, in the continuous Markovian case, there exists an almost
 explicit solution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "III.8, theorem 3"
key "Athreya2004"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 (the explicit solution gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

).
 In both these cases, the biologically interesting situation where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)=as+bs^{2}$
\end_inset

 are not interesting in the limiting clone size distribution: in continuous
 time this is an exponential, and in discrete time this can be an exponential
 (if 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

, strictly, becoming equivalent to the continuous Markov process in the
 limit) or a degenerate point mass if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)=s^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter, we tackle the problem both numerically and analytically,
 to understand 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

 as a non-linear integral transform on distributions over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{+}$
\end_inset

, between 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)$
\end_inset

.
 We seek to infer the cell cycle distribution from the measurable clone
 size distribution.
 Concretely, we attempt to invert the relationship between the cell cycle
 distribution and the clone size distribution, and investigate its stability
 and (un)suitability as a practical procedure.
 Along the way we find that not all distributions can arise as the limiting
 distribution of a super-critical branching process, and we conjecture and
 prove some properties of them.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter was inspired by conversations with the Jones team, who also
 provided the data for this theoretical detour.
\end_layout

