The inversion formula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To invert the transformation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

, defining 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)=\phi\left(e^{t}\right)$
\end_inset

 we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(t)=\int_{0}^{\infty}f\left[h\left(t-y\right)\right]g(y)\, dy,
\]

\end_inset

which is simply a convolution.
 Proceeding formally, we may take Fourier transforms and obtain the 
\emph on
Klein inversion formula
\emph default
:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The formula was independently, and to the knowledge of the author prior,
 discovered by AM Klein, 
\emph on
private correspondence
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{g}(\omega)=\frac{\tilde{h}(\omega)}{\widetilde{f\odot h}(\omega)},\label{eq:backward-eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f\odot h$
\end_inset

 is the composition of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 followed by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{t\rightarrow-\infty}h(t)=\phi(0)=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is not integrable.
 Furthermore, since 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)$
\end_inset

 considered as a distribution on the entire real line almost certainly has
 discontinuities in its derivatives at the origin, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)$
\end_inset

 will have algebraic decay for large 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)\in O\left(e^{-ct}\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, for some finite 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{h}$
\end_inset

 will only converge and thus be defined on the strip 
\begin_inset Formula $-c<\Im\left(\omega\right)<0$
\end_inset

 (the strip will be as least as wide for 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f\odot h}$
\end_inset

: the higher powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{k}$
\end_inset

 will widen the strip to 
\begin_inset Formula $kc$
\end_inset

, thus the intersection will be determined by the smallest order term in
 the expansion).
 Thus for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 to be well-defined, we require that the quotient in the inversion formula
 be analytically extended to include the real line, and give a characteristic
 function on it; in addition, it must be entirely analytic in the lower
 half-plane in order for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 to be causal, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t<0$
\end_inset

, and be asymptotically zero at negative imaginary infinity for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 to be integrable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore we are led to study what exactly is the image of the transform
 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

, equivalently the domain of the Klein formula.
 We can show than the tail of 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)$
\end_inset

 is bounded from above by any power-law decay and from below by an exponential,
 and conjecture that it is in fact exactly exponential (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "app:moment-theorems"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the requirement that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 be positive and thus a probability distribution is difficult to deal with
 analytically.
 In Fourier space, it is requiring 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 be a proper characteristic function, which has a complex and non-local
 statement via a specialisation of Bochner's theorem, specifically that
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 be positive-definite.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Positive-definiteness for a function is related to positive-definiteness
 for a matrix.
 In particular, if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 points 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\ldots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

, the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with elements 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ij}=f\left(x_{i}-x_{j}\right)$
\end_inset

 is positive semi-definite, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is positive-definite.
 Notice that as this subsumes many well-known properties of characteristic
 functions.
 For example, with 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(0)$
\end_inset

 must be real (in fact, for normalisation, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(0)=1$
\end_inset

), and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\overline{f(x)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|f(x)\right|\le f(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Higher values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 impose ever more complex and hard-to-verify conditions.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We therefore proceed by considering some specific examples to gain a better
 intuition regarding possible solutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Delta distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)=\delta(W-1)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)=e^{iu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)=e^{ie^{t}}$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{h}(\omega)=e^{\pi\omega/2}\Gamma\left(-i\omega\right)$
\end_inset

, defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\Im(\omega)<1$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(s)=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}p_{k}s^{k}
\]

\end_inset

 (notice that we do not have a constant term), 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{f\odot h}(\omega)=e^{\pi\omega/2}\Gamma\left(-i\omega\right)\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}p_{k}k^{i\omega}
\]

\end_inset

defined on the same strip.
 The quotient is then well defined:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{g}(\omega)=\frac{1}{\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}p_{k}k^{i\omega}}.
\]

\end_inset

If only one 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}$
\end_inset

 is non-zero (and therefore equal to one), we would have a well-defined
 distribution
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=\delta(t-\ln k),
\]

\end_inset

which reproduces the trivial result that a discrete time Markovian process
 with fixed outcomes in each division necessarily leads to a Dirac distribution
 as the limit.
 For a more generic 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 it does not lead to a probability distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Exponential tailed distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As conjectured, the tail of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is always exponential (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "app:moment-theorems"

\end_inset

).
 With the integral above we can consider the very general class of some
 polynomial multiplied by an exponential.
 For reasons that will become apparent, we write it as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H(W)=\sum_{k}a_{k}\frac{\lambda^{k+1}}{\Gamma(k+1)}W^{k}e^{-\lambda W}
\]

\end_inset

where normalisation requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}a_{k}=1$
\end_inset

 and unity mean requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}a_{k}(k+1)/\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, though as we shall see the latter will be automatically enforced.
 The characteristic function is very helpfully just a sum, and the complicated
 factors above all cancel:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi(u)=\sum_{k}a_{k}\left(1-\frac{iu}{\lambda}\right)^{-k-1}.
\]

\end_inset

Importantly, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\odot\phi$
\end_inset

 has the same structure, composed of a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-iu/\lambda)^{-n}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we only have to consider a single integral (convergent on 
\begin_inset Formula $-k-1<\Im\{\omega\}<0$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}e^{i\omega t}\left(1-\frac{ie^{t}}{\lambda}\right)^{-k-1}dt\\
= & \lambda^{i\omega}\int_{0}^{\infty}z^{i\omega-1}(1-iz)^{-k-1}dz\\
= & \lambda^{i\omega}e^{-\pi\omega/2}\frac{\Gamma\left(1+k-i\omega\right)\Gamma\left(i\omega\right)}{\Gamma(1+k)}\\
= & \lambda^{i\omega}e^{-\pi\omega/2}\Gamma(1-i\omega)\Gamma\left(i\omega\right)\frac{\left(1-i\omega\right)_{k}}{\Gamma(1+k)}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(z\right)_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the Pochhammer symbol.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:backward-eq"

\end_inset

, upon taking the quotient all but the last factor above cancel.
 Define the auxiliary polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $P(z)=\sum_{k}a_{k}z^{k}$
\end_inset

 (with all real coefficients) and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(z)=\frac{1}{z}f\left[zP(z)\right]$
\end_inset

 and a transform on polynomials defined by being linear and acts on each
 monomial as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{z^{k}}\Longrightarrow\frac{(1+z)_{k}}{\Gamma(k+1)}.
\]

\end_inset

Then by linearity we immediately get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{g}(\omega)=\frac{\widehat{P}(-i\omega)}{\widehat{Q}(-i\omega)}.
\]

\end_inset

Notice that the formula above is completely independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

; the correct one such that 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)$
\end_inset

 has mean of unity will be chosen.
 We can find 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 by applying the Heaviside formula to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}(iz)$
\end_inset

 (treating it as an inverse Laplace transform), and generically it will
 be a sum of exponentials (possibly with complex exponents, but always occurring
 in conjugate pairs as 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 are real), determined by the locations of zeros of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that whilst 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}(z)$
\end_inset

 cannot have any zeros on the positive real line, generically there may
 be zeros on the right half plane.
 Below, we will try and give some simple cases where this can be done and
 it yields proper cell cycle distributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest case is 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)=e^{-W}$
\end_inset

 which corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(z)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(z)=\frac{1}{z}f(z)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{g}(\omega)=\frac{1}{\sum_{k}p_{k}(1-i\omega)_{k-1}/\Gamma(k)}.
\]

\end_inset

If only one 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}$
\end_inset

 is non-zero, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=(k-1)e^{-(k-1)t}\left(e^{t}-1\right)^{k-2}.
\]

\end_inset

In particular this reproduces the result that for binary fission (
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset

) the Markovian process (
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)=e^{-t}$
\end_inset

) gives an exponential distribution in the limit.
 Biologically cells can only divide into two, so we can consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=(1-r)z+rz^{2}.$
\end_inset

 In that case, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=\frac{1}{r}e^{-t/r},
\]

\end_inset

 which is again Markovian, and, in hindsight obvious.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another simple case is when 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

-distribution; in that case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\beta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(z)=z^{\beta-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(z)=\frac{1}{z}f\left(\beta^{\beta}z^{\beta}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{g}(\omega) & =\frac{(1-i\omega)_{\beta-1}/\Gamma(\beta)}{\sum_{k}p_{k}(1-i\omega)_{k\beta-1}/\Gamma(k\beta)}\\
 & =\left[\sum_{k}p_{k}\frac{(\beta-i\omega)_{(k-1)\beta}}{(\beta)_{(k-1)\beta}}\right]^{-1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

If only one 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}$
\end_inset

 is non-zero then the poles are simple and line on the positive imaginary
 axis, and furthermore 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 is positive:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=\frac{\Gamma(k\beta)}{\Gamma(\beta)\Gamma\left[(k-1)\beta\right]}e^{-(k\beta-1)t}\left(e^{t}-1\right)^{(k-1)\beta-1}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that this reproduces, in appropriate limits, the results above for
 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)=e^{-W}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)=\delta(W-1)$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
