\begin_layout Section
A practical application
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An interesting data set come from Ruth Verstraten (Jones group) involving
 cultured human cervical cells infected by various strains of human papillomavir
us (HPV).
 We now analyse such a data set, where a particular strain (HPV16) has been
 incorporated into the genetic material of the host, leading to sustained
 proliferation in culture.
 The data was generated from 301 such single-cell derived clones cultured
 for 8 weeks; the largest of which are over 1000 cells, the smallest only
 4 cells.
 Each clone was also stained for MCM2 (minichromosome maintenance complex
 component 2) and EdU uptake over the last 24 hours, as an indication of
 proliferation (our reservations regarding markers in general notwithstanding).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A striking feature of the data is that most cells are cycling: 
\begin_inset Formula $90.9\%$
\end_inset

 are MCM2-positive, and 
\begin_inset Formula $87.4\%$
\end_inset

 are EdU-positive.
 The smallest clone with positive staining for proliferation has only 7
 cells, 5 of which are MCM2-positive, 3 are EdU-positive; the largest is
 around 1250 cells, with 1184 MCM2-positive and 1178 EdU-positive.
 Whilst we can perform analysis on only the MCM2-positive or EdU-positive
 subpopulation to ensure that we are analysing only proliferating cells,
 it is our belief that at these extremely high levels of proliferation,
 the markers are not quantitatively accurate.
 It seems to us to be more likely that 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 cells are cycling, but with very large variations in cell cycle length,
 leading to the extremely broad distribution of clone sizes with marker-positive
 cells.
 In addition, if we believe that a potential mechanism is the failure of
 cells to differentiate, when we may indeed expect some under-counting from
 markers due to cells which are 
\emph on
trying
\emph default
 to differentiate and thereby not displaying the usual molecular signs of
 cell cycle, but later on fall back into cycle again.
 In any case, our analysis below does not substantially change with the
 choice of subpopulation, and we will assume that all cells are cycling
 and allow ourselves the full data set and avoid any experimental pathology
 due to the extra complication.
\end_layout

