\begin_layout Section
Conclusion and discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have made some progress on understanding the precise class of limit distribut
ions which can arise from a 1-type supercritical branching process.
 In particular, we have shown that the tail of the distribution must be
 bounded from below by an exponential, and from above by any power-law;
 we conjecture that it must be exponential.
 We have also developed some numerical techniques which allow us to numerically
 solve 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

, and found cell cycle distributions which lead to a limit distribution
 that approximates a small data set from cultured HPV-incorporated cervical
 epithelial cells.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have a formal formula for computing the cell cycle distribution from
 a given limit distribution, providing a partial solution to the inverse
 problem.
 Directly applying the formula (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "app:examples"

\end_inset

), we can reproduce the known results for the exponential (Markovian) process,
 and the discrete time process.
 In addition, we can concretely invert the gamma distribution.
 More generally, we can formally invert distributions of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)=p(W)e^{-\lambda W}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is some polynomial, although generically they do not yield proper distributions
 upon inversion.
 We conjecture that in the space of distributions, at a generic point in
 the image of the forwards transforms, almost all directions (i.e.
 perturbations) lead off the manifold; but nevertheless, there is a countable
 number of perturbations which remain on it.
 Clearly, it would be beneficial to have a more precise characterisation
 of the manifold, and a ripe area for future theoretical work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Currently however, the formula is not best suited for direct application
 to experimental data.
 Firstly, we do not have a full characterisation of the solution space of
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

, making it difficult to project an empirical distribution into the allowed
 manifold of solutions.
 Secondly, we suspect that the inverse problem is likely to be ill-conditioned
 (in some sense yet to be made precise) or possibly even ill-posed.
 Heuristically, because the transform in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

 is continuous, there is not a sharply optimal choice for an inverse that
 optimises some cost function (likelihood, for instance).
 In particular, numerical experiments show that changes to 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 which do not significantly change extreme behaviours tends to have negligible
 effect on the outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 The situation is likely analogous to the problem of inferring a distribution
 from a finite sample, where in the absence of further constraints or strong
 priors the problem is simply ill-posed.
 It is possible that some global 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shape constraint
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 might be sufficient.
 For instance, we might impose the restriction that conditional rate of
 division is monotonically increasing as a function of cell lifetime; more
 precisely, defining the survival function as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S(t)=1-\int_{0}^{t}g(y)\, dy
\]

\end_inset

and the hazard function 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H(t)=-\frac{S^{\prime}(t)}{S(t)}=\frac{g(t)}{S(t)},
\]

\end_inset

we require that 
\begin_inset Formula $H(t)$
\end_inset

 is a non-decreasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 We suspect that a suitable discretisation of this constraint to render
 it finitary, with sufficient computation resources, could form the basis
 of a viable numerical technique to infer plausible cell cycles from measurement
s.
 More general shape constraints such as requiring 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 to be mono-modal or some fixed number of modes may also be viable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A more serious impediment may come from the restriction to 1-type branching
 processes.
 It is known 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Athreya2004"

\end_inset

 that in a multi-type, super-critical branching process, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 cell types, Malthusian parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 , branching functions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{(i)}\left(s_{1},\ldots,s_{\mu}\right)=\sum_{k_{1},\ldots,k_{\mu}}a_{k_{1},\ldots k_{\mu}}^{(i)}s_{1}^{k_{1}}\cdots s_{\mu}^{k_{\mu}}
\]

\end_inset

and lifetime functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{(i)}(t)$
\end_inset

, will converge to a clone size distribution that depends on the type of
 the initial cell, with a fixed ratio between different cell types (which
 also depend on the initial cell type).
 Specifically, letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{(i)}(u)$
\end_inset

 be the characteristic function of the limit distribution starting from
 a single cell of type 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, we have a system of coupled, non-linear integral equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi^{(i)}(u)=\int_{0}^{\infty}f^{(i)}\left[\phi^{(1)}\left(ue^{-\alpha y}\right),\ldots,\phi^{(\mu)}\left(ue^{-\alpha y}\right)\right]g^{(i)}(y)\, dy.\label{eq:horrible}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Whilst a similar formula to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:backward-eq"

\end_inset

 must exist, it would require knowledge of all the limit distributions,
 starting from different cell types.
 From an experimental point of view, this may be too much information to
 gather in the general case.
 It may still be possible to make progress on specific branching patterns,
 such as might be recapitulated by a failure to differentiate, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\rightarrow A+B$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B\rightarrow A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We cannot resist mentioning that the above example also yields one of the
 only known non-trivial solutions to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:horrible"

\end_inset

, due to John Biggins.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size normal
\emph on
Private communications.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Specifically, let 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{A}(t)=2e^{-2t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{B}(t)=e^{-t}$
\end_inset

.
 The Malthusian parameter is 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

.
 The characteristic functions are 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{A}(u)=\frac{1}{\left(1+u\right)^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{B}(u)=\frac{1}{1+u}$
\end_inset

, corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{A}(W)=We^{-W}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{B}(W)=e^{-W}$
\end_inset

.
 No analytic generalisations of this solution is known.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, it is unclear at the moment whether it may be possible to approximate
 a multi-type process as a 1-type process.
 Whilst the general case is probably answerable in the negative, we are
 more interested in cases such as above, where branching ratios are restricted
 and, e.g., one cell type is essentially a waiting room for falling back into
 cell cycle.
 In particular, we might expect some combination of multi-modal cell lifetimes
 to yield essentially the same limit distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
