\begin_layout Subsection*
Injectiveness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that two different 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 give the same 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 upon transform with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:forwards-eq"

\end_inset

.
 We may assume without loss of generality that their respective Malthusian
 parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 are equal and unity (if they are not we can simply scale the cell cycle
 distributions).
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{\infty}f\left[\phi\left(e^{t-y}\right)\right]\left[g_{1}\left(y\right)-g_{2}\left(y\right)\right]dy=0,
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Using the trick of writing 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)=\phi\left(e^{t}\right),$
\end_inset

 and applying the convolution theorem we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{f\odot h}\left(\omega\right)\left[\tilde{g}_{1}\left(\omega\right)-\tilde{g}_{2}\left(\omega\right)\right]=0.
\]

\end_inset

As noted above in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "app:examples"

\end_inset

, this will only be well defined on some open strip below the real line.
 Nevertheless, on that open strip 
