\begin_layout Section
Introduction and motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we have seen, it is possible to have a stochastic process which describes
 in quantitative detail a homoeostatic stratified epithelium such as the
 oesophageal epithelium, or skin.
 Such an approach has also seen success in other tissues which undergo continuou
s replacement and renewal throughout adult life, such as in the sperm ducts
 [???] and intestines [???].
 However, the central nervous system (CNS) is fundamentally different, as
 most neurons are not replaced during adult life.
 Thus, we are dealing with a system which is not only not in homoeostasis,
 it is also very far from equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Knowledge that a tissue is under homoeostasis significantly restricts the
 possible behaviour of cells.
 In particular, we have at our disposal 
\emph on
universal
\emph default
 scaling relations about clone sizes and clone growth rates which anchor
 our interpretation of experimental observations.
 Given the confirmation of these universal properties, we are then almost
 forced to conclude a simple, stochastic model of fate choice, with assurances
 that deviations from this model are small and that they do not impact the
 macroscopic behaviour.
 Such models are therefore not only descriptive, but also predictive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relaxing homoeostasis to mere time-translation invariance allows for much
 greater variety of behaviour.
 For example, even without interaction, we have complex relations between
 clone size distributions and cell cycle lengths.
 With interactions, we can in principle have arbitrary reaction-diffusion
 systems, which are known [???] to be Turing-complete, and are therefore
 capable of simulating any other system.
 As such, we cannot hope to quantitatively bound the errors that our assumptions
 may induce, and any model we build could in principle be only valid within
 the experimental bounds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nevertheless, we can remain guided by arguments of simplicity and concordance:
 although we cannot categorically rule out alternatives, the simplest thing
 that seems to work is probably not too far from the truth.
 More concretely, we can at least provide a 
\emph on
null hypothesis
\emph default
 on which to compare more complex models.
 In particular, we have in mind the possibility that minor modifications
 to the basic concept of stochastic, independent fate choice can recapitulate
 observed behaviour, and form the basis of such a null hypothesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The possibility that such a process could exist is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cayouette2003"

\end_inset

, which showed that isolated cultured rat retinal progenitor cells (RPCs)
 will generate the same proportions of differentiated retinal cell types
 (both neuronal and ganglial) as 
\emph on
in vivo
\emph default
.
 As isolated RPCs share little common extracellular influences, this suggests
 that the regulation for the proliferation and differentiation of progenitors
 are intrinsic.
 However, at the same time, individual clones derived from RPCs are enormous
 heterogeneous in size and composition 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Turner1987"

\end_inset

.
 Just like in epithelium, we have the dual combination of individual heterogenei
ty but tissue level regulation, seemingly without cell-cell interaction.
 We are thus encouraged to seek a stochastic model of independent RPCs,
 where individual fate choice is controlled by some fixed set of probabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We focus on an experiment which tracks by time-lapse microscopy cultured
 RPCs from day 20 embryos, from which detailed lineage trees may be reconstructe
d showing the exact time of divisions and fate outcomes.
 We show that even though the pattern of divisions seem very complex, there
 is a simple stochastic model which is consistent with the data.
 This draws heavily on the work in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gomes2010"

\end_inset

; experimental work was carried out by FLAFG, manuscript was written by
 MC, analysis by GZ and BDS, with discussions with WAH, FC and JAC.
 In what follows we will elide the exact experimental procedures, and refer
 the reader to the published work.
\end_layout

