\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We studied late stage rat retinal progenitors in culture, by reconstructing
 complete lineage trees from time-lapsed imaging.
 Because these progenitors recapitulate the same proportions of terminally
 differentiated neuron types as live systems, we are led to a model of the
 neurons as independent cells, stochastically choosing their fates.
 We find that the probabilities to renew versus differentiation is independent
 of time or generation, consistent with a model where the behaviour of progenito
rs do not change; however, this is based on only two generations, and fairly
 small samples, and we cannot categorically rule out the possibility that
 the probabilities actually evolve through this stage of development.
 Using this as a null hypothesis, we observed two decisive deviations from
 the predictions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists a strong correlation between the cell cycles of sister RPCs.
 Whilst in the current sample there are sufficiently few occurrences of
 PP divisions such that this deviation does not manifest strongly in the
 gross statistics such as clone size distributions or termination times
 across the entire sample, one might expect this effect to be significant
 during real development.
 Since there is no correlation between mother-daughter pairs, it cannot
 be due to some persistent internal biochemical state; this also rules out
 the possibility that there is some external factor which might vary between
 different physical locations in the culture, and influences the cell cycle
 length.
 The only remaining possibility is that daughter cells are somehow in a
 more similar internal state than two arbitrary progenitors, perhaps due
 to an equal sharing of the available molecular machinery from pre-mitosis,
 and that this similarity persists on the order of a cell cycle length.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Some stereotypic lineage combinations occur at a much higher frequency than
 expected.
 In other words, some progenitors are biased towards a certain pattern of
 fate outcome.
 Due to the small sample sizes, it would be difficult to draw significant
 conclusions about what exactly are the deviations --- it is within the
 realm of possibility that some of these deviations did arise by chance,
 especially since the expected number was so close to zero e.g.
 although the two occurrences of (RPC, BiMu) is statistically significant,
 it is very much borderline, and boosted by the innate discrete nature of
 counting; at the same time, it is possible that the statistical insignificance
 of (RPh, 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times$
\end_inset

RPh) triples will become significant if enough clones are collected.
 Nevertheless, we outline here some possibilities of interpretation.
 Although not the most statistically significant, the most important is
 the excess frequency of continued renewal (RPC, 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times$
\end_inset

RPC), which would imply that a individual lineages could be biased towards
 (or away from) renewal, implying non-independence of lineage-related progenitor
s.
 The lack of other signatures of non-independence prompts us to look for
 other explanations.
 One possibility is that there is in fact variation of fate choice probabilities
 with time, and some progenitors were harvested with a slightly earlier
 internal clock, which is biases them towards renewal.
 Another possibility is that there is some cell-extrinsic chemical factors
 which biases the cells, and it is the physical proximity of related cells
 which cause the correlated fate choice.
 The other significant excesses are concentrated in lineages with only amacrine
 and bipolar cells.
 A possible interpretation of these significant excesses, along with the
 not statistically significant excess of photoreceptor-only lineages, such
 as (RPh, 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times$
\end_inset

RPh), is that they are evidence of histogenesis, where certain cell types
 are predominately generated at specific points of development.
 It is known that in the full developmental history of retinal progenitors,
 ganglial cells are generated earlier, and indeed in this experiment on
 late-stage progenitors we see no production of ganglia at all; thus there
 is already some histogenesis occuring, at least differentiating between
 ganglia and neurons.
 Here, we see almost all possible temporal combinations of cell types within
 single lineages, so it is not the case that such ordering is strict, but
 is is possible that they are biased stochastically, as a set of evolving
 probabilities.
 This lends slight circumstantial evidence that the choice for renewal may
 also be time-evolving.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current experiment is limited by its size, use of culture, and inherent
 consideration of only one particular stage of retinal development.
 Nevertheless, we believe that it supports a model of stochastic fate choice,
 and in particular where the choice for renewal is decoupled from the choice
 of which cell type to differentiate into.
 Deviations from this are explainable as a result of histogenesis, where
 the specific probabilities of different fate outcomes evolve with time.
\end_layout

