\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work, we continue the themes and ideas from the previous chapter.
 In particular, we implemented and validated an 
\emph on
in vivo
\emph default
 clonal labelling system which captures retinal development in zebrafish.
 This allowed unprecedented detail of visualising the development on a clonal
 resolution, through both cohort sampling and live imaging of individual
 clones.
 Relative to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:rat-retina"

\end_inset

, we could observe the spatial as well as temporal behaviour of progenitors,
 and identified a wave which sweeps through the early retina and initiates
 proliferation of progenitors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also refined our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

null hypothesis
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of independent progenitors, through accounting for the proliferation wave
 and introducing time-dependent (but a priori fixed) relative probabilities
 for fate choice.
 We found that this simple hypothesis is in agreement with the observed
 clonal size evolution and pattern of fate choice in live imaged clones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Through the live imaging, it was also possible to study the pattern of eventual
 cell types within individual clones and their histogenesis.
 However, the relative lack of data precluded further refinement of the
 model as it would introduce a large number of parameters to adjust, diluting
 the power of the model.
 Indeed, relative to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:rat-retina"

\end_inset

, we could not image enough clones to re-do the analysis of fate choice
 triplets and look for any statistically significant deviations from a purely
 random process.
 Nevertheless, the data does show very clear signs of a progression of cell
 types, yet individual clones did not exhibit any definite ordering in cell
 type choice.
 It seems plausible that a set of evolving probabilities for cell type choice
 is sufficient to explain the observations, but it would take a much larger
 sample size to make any significant statements to that effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A significant deviation from the simple story of independent progenitors,
 which was noted in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:rat-retina"

\end_inset

, is the large correlation between the cell cycle times of sister progenitor
 cells.
 At the same time, a lack of clear correlation between unrelated cells in
 the same physical vicinity strongly suggests that the source of synchrony
 is internal, and due to sister cells somehow being in almost the same microscop
ic state upon division.
 It is unclear what other effects this extra similarity entails, since we
 did not see correlation in fate choice or terminal cell types.
 It does raise the possibility that with sufficient statistics, it may be
 possible to discern fate correlation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compared with the rat retina, zebrafish development proceeds much faster
 --- typically an initial progenitor yields three or four generations before
 a total loss of proliferation.
 In our current model, we have three distinct phases of fate choice probabilitie
s with sharp boundaries.
 This choice of parametrising the evolving stochasticity of progenitors
 was motivated by a desire for simplicity, knowing that our data will only
 have so much resolution.
 In principle, there could be a smoother or more featureful variation with
 time.
 In a larger system such as the rat, it would be interesting to know if
 the same kind of phases exist (mostly proliferative, the strongly biased
 towards asymmetric differentiation, finally strongly differentiative),
 and if so, whether the boundaries are sharp or smooth.
 An argument may be given that a phase in the middle with a large bias towards
 asymmetry makes developmental sense, as it is more robust (a more linear
 growth is less likely to catastrophically fail than an exponential one)
 both in the total size and locally (leading to less need to move cells
 around to achieve a certain average density of cells).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We reiterate that our approach with modelling developmental systems is that
 of constructing a null hypothesis, against which observations can be judged
 to be surprising.
 As such, the most direct approach to challenging the hypothesis would be
 more data (larger sample sizes), which would be able to resolve finer features
 of the development process.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A feature of the process which we have not considered in detail is the initial
 wave which signals the progenitors to begin their proliferation.
 We have only characterised the process in so far as to give a timescale
 on which we can build a model.
\end_layout

