\begin_layout Standard
Whilst detailed views on single clones are invaluable, it is essential to
 confirm that such observed clones are representative of the growth of the
 whole structure.
 Some marking protocols make preferentially label particular cell types
 or cells in particular states, or even influence cell fate through modified
 fate choice or even apoptosis.
 As an aside, the marker system used here is actually the second pass at
 such a system, the first one based around a Gal4 driver (MAZe:nlsRFP, see
 below) apparently causing cell death, and leading to a 6 month delay in
 the project.
 Sadly, it is hard to confirm representativeness of clones without first
 gathering sufficient numbers of them, thus even in retrospect it is unclear
 what could have been done to avoid the blind-alley.
 In this case, individual clones simply did not appear anomalous, even though
 in aggregate they differed significantly.
 In any case, here we lay out our consistency checks which aim to show that
 the MAZe:Kaede clones are indeed representative of the overall growth of
 the retina.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we need accurate measurements on the overall kinetics of the whole
 retina, in particular the number of cells over time, in particular by measuring
 the volume and cell density.
 The volume was obtained by fitting a surface to a three dimensional (3D)
 reconstruction of the retina at distinct developmental stages.
 The density was estimated from confocal sagittal sections and direct measuremen
ts of cell diameter perpendicular to the sections.
 Specifically, we assumed that cells with their centre within a perpendicular
 radius of the confocal plane (which is assumed to be of zero depth) will
 show up in the section, leading to a viable 3D volume as the denominator.
 These results revealed that the embryonic retina consists of approximately
 1,800 cells at 24 hpf, rising to approximately 11,000 cells at 48 hpf,
 and 21,000 cells at 72 hpf.
 This translates to a 6- and 12-fold increase, respectively.
 
\end_layout

