\begin_layout Chapter
Conclusions and Further Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this thesis, we have tried to demonstrate the role that quantitative
 clonal lineage tracing may play in dissecting the underlying cell kinetics,
 in both homoeostasis as well as highly non-equilibrium situations.
 In particular, we have focused on the utility of being able to use the
 information in the entire 
\emph on
distribution
\emph default
 of clone sizes, as opposed to merely the mean or variance.
 We have mostly been preoccupied with models of independent stochastic cells,
 both for their analytical tractability but also the relatively few parameters
 necessary to fit against experimental data; at the present level of experimenta
lly achievable precision, these simple models appear sufficient to form
 a basis for understanding observed behaviour.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We extended the existing paradigm in epithelial tissue with quantitative
 methods which allow precision measurements of cell cycle rate and, importantly,
 branching ratios.
 Importantly, the precision allows us to rule out certain forms of independence
 between daughter cells.
 The level of precision available is sufficient to complement accepted methods
 of biochemical staining as the primary way through which quantitative measureme
nts may be carried out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We found that a stochastic model of fate choice is capable of describing
 retinal neurons in development, both 
\emph on
in vitro
\emph default
 and in live embryos.
 In this domain, the main utility of the model is as a null hypothesis against
 which we can understand if an observed collective behaviour is the result
 of some precise regulated process or merely a statistically likely outcome
 (for example, the complex pattern of potential cell types that result from
 a given retinal progenitor cell).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We extended theoretical understanding of supercritical, Markov branching
 processes, specifically the link between cell cycle distributions and limit
 distributions of clone sizes.
 We find some bounds on theoretically allowed limit distributions and a
 formula for potentially computing cell cycle distributions from measured
 limited distributions.
 We also applied this to a small data set on hyper-proliferating cultured
 human cervical epithelium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differentiating between different microscopic/biochemical models is still
 beyond the reach of the present work.
 Nevertheless, we do not believe this to be a fundamental obstacle.
 Whilst observations of universal behaviour (in the sense of statistical
 mechanics) are the most reliable evidence of a model, it is the non-universal
 deviations which allow fine dissection of the underlying mechanism.
 The main obstacle seems to be one of gathering sufficient statistics for
 the non-universal behaviour to be distinguishable from noise.
 To that end, a major area of further work must be improvements in experimental
 efficiency, as well as computational efficiency in mapping observed deviations
 to concrete models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For instance, it may be possible to say something regarding potential cell-cell
 interactions.
 Throughout this work, we focused on models where cells are statistically
 independent, apart from potential division synchrony between daughters
 where noted.
 One can imagine at least two biologically interesting ways in which this
 assumption could be violated: daughter cells begin their lives in a closer
 internal state than two arbitrary cells, which could lead to correlations
 between nearby cells (over and above simply being in similar external environme
nts), or nearby cells could actively inhibit each other via cell-cell signals.
 It is known that in two dimensions, the latter belongs properly in a different
 universality class than branching processes, but the corrections are only
 logarithmic with time, which may be too close to a constant for biologically
 accessible timescales.
 It may be more possible to instead distinguish between these possibilities
 with non-universal corrections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the primary driving force behind many of the works in this thesis
 has been novel experiments, which yield new forms of data that have no
 established method of analysis.
 We want to emphasise the importance of taking the data as the primary object
 of study, rather than trying to gang-press some particular or fashionable
 method into service.
 As such, future work will likely be dominated by the need to understand
 and refine the experimental procedures which generate novel types of data.
\end_layout

