\begin_layout Itemize
In intestinal crypts, there has been a long standing question of what exactly
 is the proliferation hierarchy.
 Clonal labelling techniques 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lopez-Garcia2010"

\end_inset

 suggest that there is an equipotent population of progenitors which undergo
 stochastic renewal and differentiation, constrained to preserving the populatio
n number by homoeostasis.
 However, because of the one-dimensional nature of the anatomical niche
 that they occupy (distributed in a ring), the scaling dynamics is different
 from oesophagus and recapitulates the expected 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{t}$
\end_inset

 growth of average clone size instead.
 However, it does also appear that there exist measurable states of the
 progenitors which influences the likelihood of division 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Snippert2010"

\end_inset

, tied to the expression of Lgr5.
 It remains unclear to what extent the states are truly distinct, or if
 cells are constantly changing their internal states on a timescale far
 smaller than a typical cell cycle, and the observed expression levels are
 merely correlated with this internal chaotic motion.
 The Clevers group has also used clonal analysis to quantitatively analyses
 the breakdown of homoeostasis in tumour formation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Snippert2014"

\end_inset

.
